In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** in `MauiProgram.cs` (or your app builder setup) via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android
        .OnPause(activity =>
        {
            // runs on Android pause
        })
        .OnStop(activity =>
        {
            // runs on Android stop
        }));
#endif

#if IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios
        .DidEnterBackground(app =>
        {
            // runs when iOS app enters background
        }));
#endif
});
```

**Key points:**

- Add `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` to your `MauiAppBuilder` chain in `CreateMauiApp()`.
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.
- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnCreate`, `OnDestroy`, etc.
- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.
- The delegates receive the native platform object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call native APIs directly.
